==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*doxtrō-'', from Indo-European ''*dhuktēr''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[dohtar]] (Dutch [[dochter]]), Old High German [[tochter]] (German [[Tochter]]), Old Norse [[dottir|dóttir]] (Swedish [[dotter]]), Gothic [[𐌳𐌰𐌿𐌷𐍄𐌰𐍂]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[θυγατηρ|θυγάτηρ]], Lithuanian [[dukte]], Old Church Slavonic [[дъшти]] (Russian [[дочь]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'doxtor/

